snippet.textDisplay:
An attorney who had travelled to Europe last week went to a NYC emergency room because he had flu symptoms and was concerned he had Coronavirus. He sat on a litter in the hallway amongst other patients and healthcare providers for six hours before testing negative for the flu. Doctors told him they were unable to test him for Coronavirus, so he left. He sourced a drive-thru testing location in Greenwich, CT and travelled there to get the test. He ultimately tested POSITIVE for Coronavirus. Apparently, there was no issue with not-enough-tests in Greenwich, one of the wealthiest places on Earth.
First of all, going to a crowded city emergency department, unless you're having serious symptoms like difficulty breathing, is exactly what we're NOT supposed to do if we think we may have the virus. The hospital SHOULD have waved this person off to keep others, including at-risk folks, from possibly getting infected. Secondly, at a time when we're seeing professional athletes getting what seems like unlimited access to what limited testing there is, it sure seems like gross inequality in public health access that a place like Greenwich CT is able to offer virtually unlimited testing when hot spots like New York City are not.
This terrifying crisis is going to expose the brutal lack of equality in our healthcare system as large groups of vulnerable people get exposed to Coronavirus and require hospitalization. The over 120 thousand homeless in California for example, are going to be at greater risk of infection since it will be much more difficult for them to shelter in place. Actual homeless shelters are going to be dangerous sources of public transmission because of how close in proximity people are to one another. This problem could easily be the cause for overwhelm at area hospitals as individuals contact the virus and develope symptoms. There's got to be a way to get these people housed, in tents if need be, in a way that enables minimal separation distance and at least basic sanitation. How we treat the most vulnerable in our society in these coming weeks and months, will tell a lot about the United States as a country.
